Select oil based primer paint for the first coat. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/8\/8a\/Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-1Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/8\/8a\/Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-1Bullet1.jpg\/v4-760px-Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

If you are painting over stained cedar or redwood, ask an experienced paint store clerk to help you choose the proper primer to cover those woods. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/6f\/Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-1Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/6f\/Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-1Bullet2.jpg\/v4-760px-Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Choose either oil-base paint or acrylic latex paint for the second coat and finish coats. Read the label on latex paints to make sure they can be painted over oil primer. Choose exterior or interior paint depending on where the door surface will be. A gloss or semi-gloss finish is best for exterior surfaces. Semi-gloss or “eggshell” finish is best for interior door sides. Choose an acrylic clear sealer to cover the paint after it dries to prolong the life of the paint and make it easier to clean. For an average-sized door, you will need 1 quart of each kind of paint and sealer. (You will need 2 quarts of finish paint if each side of the door is a different color.)

Leave one half of the hinge attached to the doorframe to make it easier to re-hang the door. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7e/Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7e/Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you can’t remove the door for some reason you will need to protect the doorframe and nearby walls with painters tape. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e9/Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e9/Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Sand to remove the gloss and slightly roughen the surface, not to remove all the previous coatings of sealer or stain. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0c/Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-6Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0c/Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-6Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Be careful not to gouge or make grooves when sanding. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/54/Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-6Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/54/Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-6Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use a wire brush to rough up grooved or ornate design areas on the door. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/83/Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-6Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-6Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/83/Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-6Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Paint-a-Stained-Door-Step-6Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
